<p>
<h1>List APIs</h1> 
</p>

<p><b>API Platform Base Path:</b> <code>https://api.enterprise.apigee.com/v1/o/{org_name}</code></p>

<div class="row">
	<div class="span6" style="width:340px;">

		<p><b>API Resource Path:</b> <code>/apis</code></p>
		<p><b>Description:</b> Gets all APIs in an organization. The names in the list map to the names defined in the API proxy configuration for each API.
		</p>
	</div>

	<div class="span6" style="width:340px;">
<table>		
	<tbody><tr><td><b>Verb:</b></td> <td><span class="verb-GET">GET</span></td></tr>
	<tr><td><b>Auth:</b></td> <td>Basic Auth</td></tr>


		<tr><td style="vertical-align:top"><b>Media types:</b></td>  <td>
<div class="content_type" id="content_type_1">
application/json
</div>
<div class="content_type" id="content_type_2">
text/xml
</div></td></tr>

		</tbody>
</table>


	</div>
</div>

<div class="span18">
	

		<div class="prerequisites"><b>For detailed instructions on using the "List APIs" method, see the <a href="http://apigee.com/docs/api/content/quickstarts/local-api-development">Developer Guide Topic</a> in the <a href="http://apigee.com/docs/enterprise/content/developer_guide">API Proxy Developer Guide</a>.</b></div>

		
	<p><b>Overview: </b>Returns a list of all APIs in an organization.</p>
	

	<b>Sample Request:</b>
	<pre class="terminal">$ curl -X GET -H "Accept:application/json" \ 
https://api.enterprise.apigee.com/v1/o/{org_name}/apis \
-u myname:mypass</div>


<b>Sample Response:</b> 
	<pre>[ "api1", "api2", "api3" ]</pre>


	
</div>
            </div>
        </div><!--/row-->
